column3: Attempted access to non-existent CSRs will generate an illegal instruction exception
column4: Demonstrate that all illegal CSR accesses generate an exception with mcause set to 0x2

column3: mtvec provides the starting value of the Interrupt Vector Table as well as the mode number at the time. Mode number is not relevant to exceptions as it only affects the value jumped to by interrupts.
column4: Show that exceptions jump to the base value defined in mtvec

column3: When an instruction address has a trigger set for it and mcontrol.action==0 then a breakpoint exception is taken
column4: Breakpoint exception is entered with mcause set to 0x3

column3: If an EBREAK or C.EBREAK is executed and dcsr.ebreakm is 0 then a breakpoint exception is taken
column4: Breakpoint exception is entered with mcause set to 0x3

column3: When a load/store/amo address has a trigger set for it and mcontrol.action==0 then a breakpoint exception is taken
column4: Breakpoint exception is entered with mcause set to 0x3

column3: If execution is attempted in a PMA region set to I/O, an instruction access fault exception is taken
column4: Exception is entered with mcause set to 0x1

column3: If an instruction fetch receives a bus error and is actually executed, an instruction bus fault exception is taken
column4: Exception is entered with mcause set to 0x30

column3: If an ECALL is executed then an environment call exception is taken
column4: Exception is entered with mcause set to 0xB

column3: A non-natively aligned store to I/O memory (via PMA attribution) will result in a store acccess fault exception
column4: Exception is entered with mcause set to 0x7

column3: An atomic write to a non-Atomic region (via PMA attribution) will result in a store access fault exception
column4: Exception is entered with mcause set to 0x7

column3: A store conditional to a non-Atomic region (via PMA attribution) will result in a store access fault exception
column4: Exception is entered with mcause set to 0x7

column3: A non-natively aligned load from I/O memory (via PMA attribution) will result in a load access fault exception
column4: Exception is entered with mcause set to 0x5

column3: A Load Reserved from a non-Atomic region (via PMA attribution) will result in a load access fault exception
column4: Exception is entered with mcause set to 0x5

column3:
- Synchronous exceptions are of lower priority than all interrupts.
- Exception priority (high to low)
-- code=3 (Instruction address breakpoint)
-- code=1 (PMA instruction access fault)
-- code=48 (instruction bus fault)
-- code=2 (illegal instruction)
-- code=11 (Environment call)
-- code=3 (Environment break)
-- code=3 (Load/store/amo address breakpoint)
-- code=7 (PMA store/AMO access fault)
-- code=5 (PMA load access fault)
column4: Attempt execution of an instruction with instruction address breakpoint at the same time as one of the other reasons for exception occurred, for each of the other exceptions (pma instr acc fault, instr bus fault, illegal, …)
Attempt execution of an instruction with instruction bus fault combined with one of each of: Illegal instr, data-side address breakpoint, pma access fault
For each of illegal instruction, ecall, and ebreak, attempt execution of it in combination with a data-side breakpoint
Attempt execution of an instruction with a load/store/amo address breakpoint which would otherwise cause a PMA store/AMO access fault and also one which would cause a PMA load access fault
